  "prompt": "Can you mix hair dye with your conditioner?",
  "response": "Yes, you can mix hair dye with your conditioner, but there are some important considerations to keep in mind:\n\n### **Why Mix Hair Dye with Conditioner?**\nMixing hair dye with conditioner is often done to create a more diluted, subtle color or to refresh or tone your hair color without using full-strength hair dye. It's commonly used for:\n- **Toning:** Neutralizing brassy or unwanted tones (e.g., mixing a purple or blue toner with conditioner for blonde or gray hair).\n- **Color Refreshing:** Adding a hint of color to faded hair.\n- **DIY Hair Mask:** Creating a more gentle, conditioning treatment with a tint of color.\n\n### **How to Do It:**\n1. **Choose the Right Products:**\n   - Use a semi-permanent or demi-permanent hair dye (not permanent dye) because these are designed to deposit color without developer.\n   - Use a plain, **without silicones or heavy oils**, as these can interfere with color absorption.\n\n2. **Mixing Ratio:**\n   - Start with a small amount of hair dye and mix it into a larger amount of conditioner (e.g., 1 part dye to 3 or 4 parts conditioner). Adjust the ratio depending on how intense you want the color.\n\n3. **Application:**\n   - Apply the mixture to clean, damp hair.\n   - Leave it on for **10-30 minutes**, depending on the desired intensity and the dye's instructions.\n   - Rinse thoroughly with cool water to seal the color.\n\n### **Things to Consider:**\n- **Patch Test:** Always do a patch test to check for allergies or unexpected results.\n- **Color Outcome:** The result will be more subtle than using full-strength dye, so don't expect drastic changes.\n- **Conditioner Type:** Avoid conditioners with heavy oils, silicones, or moisturizing agents, as they can prevent the dye from adhering properly.\n- **Hair Type:** This method works best on **pre-lightened or porous hair**, as it absorbs color more easily.\n\n### **When Not to Mix:**\n- **Permanent Hair Dye:** Do not mix permanent hair dye with conditioner unless you're following a specific expert recommendation. Permanent dye requires a developer, and altering the formula can lead to unpredictable results.\n- **Damaged Hair:** If your hair is already very damaged, consult a professional before applying any dye, even in a diluted form.\n\nMixing hair dye with conditioner can be a great way to experiment with color or maintain your shade, but proceed with caution and always follow the dye manufacturer's guidelines.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
